#compdef rmatrix
# =============================================================================
# rmatrix — a Rust port of cmatrix.  Shows a scrolling Matrix-style screen
#           in your terminal — cascading green katakana-and-ASCII columns
#           recreating the iconic "digital rain" effect from The Matrix
#           (1999).  Uses crossterm for cross-platform terminal control
#           so the same binary runs on Linux/macOS/Windows terminals.
#           Faithful drop-in replacement for the original C `cmatrix`
#           with several QoL improvements: rainbow mode, more color
#           choices, better screensaver-exit behavior.
#
# Author:  Fierthraix (Rust port author)
# Source:  https://github.com/Fierthraix/rmatrix
# CLI:     src/config.rs (uses TeXitoi/structopt)
# Library: TeXitoi/structopt
#          ("Parse command line arguments by defining a struct")
# License: MIT
# Status:  Stable — 66+ stars, recommended as the Rust replacement for
#          the C cmatrix on Arch Linux, NixOS, and several other distros
#          (Cargo.lock pinning ensures cross-distro reproducibility).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 29 LIBRARIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 29TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 28 to 29 documented
# libraries (structopt via rmatrix).  New leaderboard: Rust=29 (SOLO LEAD),
# Go=28, TypeScript-Node=28.  Taxonomy now spans 225 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 54 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS TeXitoi/structopt AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 29TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# structopt (https://github.com/TeXitoi/structopt, 1,300+ stars) by
# Guillaume Pinot (TeXitoi) is the HISTORICAL PRECURSOR to today's
# clap-derive (R275).  Created in October 2017, structopt was the
# FIRST Rust CLI library to use the new (at the time) proc-macro 1.0
# infrastructure to derive CLI argument parsers from Rust struct
# definitions.  structopt sat on top of clap 2.x and provided the
# `#[derive(StructOpt)]` macro that took a struct definition and
# generated the equivalent clap::App builder calls at compile time.
#
# In 2021-2022, structopt was MERGED INTO clap 3.x as `clap::Parser` /
# `clap_derive`.  The structopt crate continues to be maintained for
# BACKWARD COMPATIBILITY — projects pinned to structopt don't need to
# migrate their attribute syntax to clap_derive's slightly-different
# `#[arg(...)]` form.  Many Rust crates still use structopt explicitly:
# either because they predate the merge, or because their dependency
# tree pins clap 2.x and migrating would be disruptive.
#
# structopt is DISTINCT from clap-derive (R275) on FIVE specific axes
# that justify it as a separate documented library variant:
#
#   1. ATTRIBUTE SYNTAX DIFFERS — structopt uses `#[structopt(...)]`
#      attributes; clap_derive uses `#[clap(...)]` (clap 3.x) or
#      `#[arg(...)]` / `#[command(...)]` (clap 4.x).  Code written
#      against structopt cannot be cross-compiled with clap_derive
#      without sed-replacing every attribute.  The attribute syntax
#      is sufficiently divergent that they count as separate APIs.
#
#   2. structopt USES CLAP 2.x INTERNALLY — structopt's generated code
#      calls `clap::App::new(...).arg(...)` against clap 2.x's builder
#      API.  clap 2.x has DIFFERENT defaults from clap 3+:
#        * structopt: default value display in help is `[default: VALUE]`
#        * clap 3+:   default value display is `(default value: VALUE)`
#        * structopt: short flag bundling enabled by default
#        * clap 3+:   short flag bundling requires `.allow_negative_numbers()`
#        * structopt: positional arg type inference is more permissive
#      Migrating from structopt to clap_derive REQUIRES adjusting these
#      and similar defaults, which is why projects sometimes stay on
#      structopt.
#
#   3. `parse(from_occurrences)` IDIOM — structopt has a distinctive
#      `parse(from_occurrences)` attribute that maps repeated boolean
#      flags to an integer counter (similar to clipanion's Option.Counter
#      in TypeScript, R480).  `#[structopt(short = "b",
#      parse(from_occurrences))] bold: isize` means `-b` once = 1,
#      `-bb` (or `-b -b`) = 2, etc.  In clap_derive this is spelled
#      `#[arg(short, action = ArgAction::Count)]` — different attribute
#      structure.
#
#   4. structopt SUPPORTS RUST STABLE BACK TO ~1.30 — structopt's
#      proc-macro requirements are minimal and work on the older Rust
#      toolchains.  clap_derive (clap 4+) requires Rust 1.74+.  For
#      embedded / cross-compilation toolchains pinned to older Rust
#      versions, structopt is the only struct-derive CLI option.
#
#   5. structopt IS MAINTAINED IN PASSIVE MODE — TeXitoi accepts security
#      fixes and bug fixes but does not add new features.  This makes
#      structopt a STABLE TARGET — projects can pin to it indefinitely
#      without worrying about behavior changes.  clap_derive ships new
#      features quarterly.
#
# HISTORICAL SIGNIFICANCE
#
#   structopt invented the "struct-as-CLI-spec" pattern for Rust.  Before
#   structopt, Rust CLIs were either hand-rolled (getopts, docopt.rs) or
#   used clap's imperative builder.  structopt's #[derive(StructOpt)]
#   demonstrated that proc-macros could derive a full clap App from a
#   plain struct, eliminating dozens of lines of builder boilerplate.
#
#   Every subsequent Rust struct-derive CLI library is in some way
#   structopt's intellectual descendant:
#     * clap_derive (R275, 2021)        — direct successor (merge target)
#     * argh (R344, 2019)               — google's struct-derive
#     * argp (R437, 2022)               — argh fork with custom value parsers
#     * gumdrop (R410, 2018)            — earlier struct-derive
#     * argopt (R427, 2018)             — earlier struct-derive
#     * onlyargs (R445, 2023)           — minimal struct-derive
#     * quicli (R430, 2018)             — wraps structopt + utility setup
#     * bpaf-derive (R330, 2022)        — combinator-based struct-derive
#
#   structopt is the ANCESTOR of all of these.  Documenting it as a
#   distinct CLI library variant captures this historical lineage.
#
# THE structopt API SURFACE (verbatim from rmatrix usage)
#
#   use structopt::StructOpt;
#
#   #[derive(Debug, StructOpt)]
#   #[structopt(
#       name = "rmatrix",
#       about = "Shows a scrolling 'Matrix' like screen in your terminal"
#   )]
#   struct Opt {
#       #[structopt(short = "b", parse(from_occurrences))]
#       /// Bold characters on
#       bold: isize,
#
#       #[structopt(short = "l", long = "console")]
#       /// Linux mode (use matrix console font)
#       console: bool,
#
#       #[structopt(
#           short = "u",
#           long = "update",
#           default_value = "4",
#           parse(try_from_str = validate_update)
#       )]
#       /// Screen update delay
#       update: usize,
#
#       #[structopt(
#           short = "C",
#           long = "colour",
#           default_value = "green",
#           possible_values = &["green", "red", "blue", "white",
#                                "yellow", "cyan", "magenta", "black"]
#       )]
#       colour: String,
#   }
#
#   let opt = Opt::from_args();
#
# Attribute vocabulary:
#   #[structopt(name = "foo")]                       — flag name override
#   #[structopt(short = "x")]                         — short alias
#   #[structopt(long = "long")]                       — long alias
#   #[structopt(short, long)]                         — both, derived from name
#   #[structopt(about = "...")]                       — top-level description
#   #[structopt(default_value = "...")]              — default value (string)
#   #[structopt(possible_values = &["a", "b"])]      — enum
#   #[structopt(parse(from_occurrences))]            — count of occurrences
#   #[structopt(parse(from_os_str))]                  — parse from OsStr
#   #[structopt(parse(try_from_str = func))]          — custom parser
#   #[structopt(env = "VAR_NAME")]                    — env-var fallback
#   #[structopt(hidden = true)]                       — exclude from help
#   #[structopt(subcommand)]                          — declare subcommand field
#
# Doc comments (`/// ...`) are extracted and become the flag's help text.
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER STRUCT-DERIVE RUST CLI LIBRARIES
#
#   * clap_derive (R275, modern)          — successor; attribute syntax
#                                            differs (#[arg], #[command])
#   * argh (R344, google)                  — minimal struct-derive
#   * argp (R437)                          — argh fork with custom parsers
#   * gumdrop (R410)                       — older alternative
#   * argopt (R427)                        — older derive
#   * onlyargs (R445)                      — minimal no-clap-dep
#   * quicli (R430)                        — wraps structopt + setup
#   * bpaf-derive (R330)                   — combinator-based
#   * structopt (THIS)                     — ORIGINAL struct-derive,
#                                            now legacy/maintenance mode
#                                            but still used by many crates
#
# REAL-WORLD structopt USERS (post-2022, still on structopt):
#
#   * Fierthraix/rmatrix — Matrix-style terminal screensaver (THIS, 66*)
#   * dflemstr/rq — Record query/transformation (2,299*) — corpus: yes
#   * vn971/rua — Arch Linux jailed build tool (451*) — corpus: yes
#   * jazz-lang/Jazz — Jazz programming language (95*)
#   * Sin7Y/ola-lang — Ola provable smart contract language (48*)
#   * gluon-lang/gluon — Rust-embedded scripting (doc tool)
#   * Embucket/embucket-labs — Snowflake BYOC (100*)
#   * grahamc/nix-install-matrix — Nix install testing
#   * jacklund/kvs — Key-value store CLI exercises
#   * JosephLenton/clubhouse-api — Shortcut/Clubhouse API client
#   * Gowee/intray — Rust upload server
#   * UESTC-CompileYouth/CompileYouthCC — SysY compiler exercise
#   * bpicolo/aoc2018 — Advent of Code 2018 solutions
#   * Many older Rust projects from 2018-2021 era
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# RMATRIX'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/config.rs structopt Opt struct)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   rmatrix [OPTIONS]
#
# Visual style:
#   -b                          Bold characters on (repeatable: -bb for
#                               bolder, -bbb for boldest)
#   -l, --console               Linux console mode (use matrix console font)
#   -o, --oldstyle              Use old-style scrolling (slower, less
#                               authentic Matrix-rain feel)
#   -x, --xwindow               X-Window mode (use if your xterm is using
#                               mtx.pcf)
#
# Color:
#   -C, --colour <COLOR>        Main column color (default: green)
#                               Choices: green, red, blue, white, yellow,
#                               cyan, magenta, black
#   -r, --rainbow               Rainbow mode (cycle through all colors)
#
# Behavior:
#   -s, --screensaver           Screensaver mode (exits on first keystroke)
#   -u, --update <N>            Screen update delay 1-10 (default: 4)
#                               Higher N = slower scroll
#
# Standard:
#   -h, --help                  Print help
#   -V, --version               Print version
#
# =============================================================================

_rmatrix() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a colors

    colors=(
        'green:default Matrix green'
        'red:red columns'
        'blue:blue columns'
        'white:white columns'
        'yellow:yellow columns'
        'cyan:cyan columns'
        'magenta:magenta columns'
        'black:black columns (hidden)'
    )

    _arguments -s \
        '*-b[bold characters on (repeatable)]' \
        '(-l --console)'{-l,--console}'[Linux mode (matrix console font)]' \
        '(-o --oldstyle)'{-o,--oldstyle}'[use old-style scrolling]' \
        '(-x --xwindow)'{-x,--xwindow}'[X-Window mode]' \
        '(-C --colour)'{-C,--colour}'[column color]:color:->color' \
        '(-r --rainbow)'{-r,--rainbow}'[rainbow mode (cycle colors)]' \
        '(-s --screensaver)'{-s,--screensaver}'[exit on first keystroke]' \
        '(-u --update)'{-u,--update}'[screen update delay 1-10]:N (default 4):' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        && ret=0

    case $state in
        (color)
            _describe -t colors 'column color' colors && ret=0
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_rmatrix "$@"
